{"id": "2026-07-22-science-heat-flows-in-quantized-steps-through-graphene-s", "date": "2026-07-22", "stream": "science", "headline": "Heat flows in quantized steps through graphene's fractal quantum-Hall states", "summary": "Johnson-noise thermometry shows thermal conductance is quantized in units of the thermal conductance quantum, tracking Chern numbers, in a bilayer-graphene moire superlattice's Hofstadter states.", "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.19205", "source_domain": "arxiv.org", "tier": "T1", "tags": ["preprint"], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "In the quantum Hall effect - the regime where a cold two-dimensional electron sheet in a strong magnetic field carries current losslessly along its edges - electrical conduction comes in exact, universal quantized steps. Whether heat is carried the same universal way in the richer Hofstadter states (the fractal energy spectrum electrons form when a magnetic field and a periodic moire lattice act on them together) had never been tested. Using Johnson-noise thermometry - reading temperature off the faint electrical noise that any warm conductor emits - the team measured the thermal conductance of quantum-Hall, Chern-insulator, and interaction-driven symmetry-broken states in a bilayer-graphene/boron-nitride superlattice (moire wavelength about 14 nm), and found it quantized in units of the thermal conductance quantum, tracking each state's Chern number (the integer that labels its topology).", "why": "It shows these exotic topological states move heat as cleanly and universally as they move charge, confirming their fundamental nature and giving a probe of edge modes that ordinary electrical measurements can miss.", "thread_id": "2026-07-22-science-heat-flows-in-quantized-steps-through-graphene-s", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-22", "event_date": "2026-07-21", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["Indian Institute of Science", "NIMS"], "entities": ["Indian Institute of Science", "NIMS", "graphene"]}
{"id": "2026-07-22-science-earth-s-inner-core-may-be-more-than-1-000-c-cool", "date": "2026-07-22", "stream": "science", "headline": "Earth's inner core may be more than 1,000 C cooler than the textbook value", "summary": "Science reports diamond-anvil measurements putting iron's melting point at inner-core-boundary pressure near 4,420-5,220 K, over 1,000 C below the standard estimate, easing the geodynamo puzzle.", "url": "https://www.science.org/content/article/earth-s-core-may-be-far-cooler-scientists-thought", "source_domain": "science.org", "tier": "T2", "tags": ["single-source"], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Science reports new high-pressure laboratory measurements putting the melting point of iron at inner-core-boundary conditions at roughly 4,420-5,220 K - more than 1,000 C below the ~5,500 C usually quoted - implying a cooler core than the standard picture. The team squeezed iron between diamond anvils to near two million atmospheres (comparable to the outer core) and, instead of laser-heating it, drove it with microsecond electrical pulses for tighter temperature control. A cooler core is more permissive of a thermally driven geodynamo (the churning liquid-iron engine that generates Earth's magnetic field): per the report, core cooling alone could have powered the field for most of Earth's history, until the solid inner core began to freeze a little over half a billion years ago. I could not reach the primary paper or the article's full text from the sandbox, so this rests on Science's account via search snippet - treat the exact figures as provisional pending the paper.", "why": "The core's temperature sets the energy budget for Earth's magnetic shield and the age of the solid inner core; shaving 1,000 C off it reshuffles both.", "thread_id": "2026-07-22-science-earth-s-inner-core-may-be-more-than-1-000-c-cool", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-22", "event_date": "2026-07-21", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "entities": ["Earth", "geodynamo"]}
{"id": "2026-07-22-science-a-single-waxy-molecule-not-just-bullying-keeps-n", "date": "2026-07-22", "stream": "science", "headline": "A single waxy molecule, not just bullying, keeps naked mole-rat queens in charge", "summary": "Nature study identifies isopropyl myristate, an ester enriched in queens, as the olfactory signal that suppresses reproduction in subordinate naked mole-rats.", "url": "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-026-10772-5", "source_domain": "nature.com", "tier": "T1", "tags": [], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Naked mole-rats are one of the very few eusocial mammals: a single queen breeds while every other female stays infertile, and how the queen enforces that had been unclear. This study names the signal - isopropyl myristate, a low-volatility ester (a waxy, barely-evaporating oily molecule) strongly enriched in queens and nearly absent from non-breeders. Olfactory neurons in the nose and brain detect it; exposure shifts the hormones prolactin and progesterone in subordinates to suppress their reproduction and provokes avoidance in high-ranking rivals. In behavioural tests, adding the ester daily to a queenless colony prevented a new queen from emerging, while withdrawing it triggered aggression and reproductive competition. The same molecule showed up in breeding females of related Fukomys mole-rats, hinting the mechanism is shared across the group.", "why": "It gives a concrete molecular handle - a chemical the animals can smell - on how a mammalian society centrally controls who gets to reproduce, rather than chalking it up to social stress alone.", "thread_id": "2026-07-22-science-a-single-waxy-molecule-not-just-bullying-keeps-n", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-22", "event_date": "2026-07-15", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["Max Delbrück Center", "Max Planck Institute for Brain Research", "University of Pretoria"], "entities": ["naked mole-rat", "isopropyl myristate", "Max Delbrück Center"]}
{"id": "2026-07-22-science-the-largest-genetic-study-of-borderline-personal", "date": "2026-07-22", "stream": "science", "headline": "The largest genetic study of borderline personality disorder finds its first solid signals", "summary": "A GWAS of 12,339 cases identifies 11 genomic loci and 9 risk genes for borderline personality disorder, with 17.3% SNP heritability - the first robust common-variant signals.", "url": "https://www.nature.com/articles/s41588-026-02654-3", "source_domain": "nature.com", "tier": "T1", "tags": [], "topics": ["science", "health"], "importance": 2, "display_body": "Borderline personality disorder (BPD) has been understudied genetically and often framed as purely a product of environment. This genome-wide association study - a scan of the whole genome for common DNA variants statistically linked to a trait - pooled 12,339 cases against about 1.04 million controls, with a separate replication sample, and identified 11 independent genomic loci and 9 risk genes. It reports a SNP-based heritability of 17.3% (the share of variation these common variants can account for) and polygenic scores that predict about 4.6% of the risk - a real biological signal but far from an individual-level test. All participants were of European ancestry, a genuine limitation on how broadly the results generalise, and the signals overlap with those of other psychiatric and some physical conditions.", "why": "It is the first robust evidence of a common-variant genetic contribution to a heavily stigmatised condition, supporting a biological component and shared architecture with other disorders - without implying any near-term diagnostic use.", "thread_id": "2026-07-22-science-the-largest-genetic-study-of-borderline-personal", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-22", "event_date": "2026-07-20", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["Heidelberg University", "Central Institute of Mental Health", "Broad Institute"], "entities": ["borderline personality disorder", "Heidelberg University", "Broad Institute"]}
{"id": "2026-07-22-science-beta-pictoris-d-the-faintest-exoplanet-ever-dire", "date": "2026-07-22", "stream": "science", "headline": "Beta Pictoris d: the faintest exoplanet ever directly imaged from the ground", "summary": "ESO's VLT, with an independent JWST detection, directly images a third planet in the Beta Pictoris system - a ~2.4 Jupiter-mass gas giant and the faintest exoplanet yet imaged from Earth.", "url": "https://www.eso.org/public/news/eso2609/", "source_domain": "eso.org", "tier": "T1", "tags": [], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 3, "display_body": "Astronomers have directly imaged a third planet around Beta Pictoris, a young star 63 light-years away whose disk and planets are a benchmark for how planetary systems form. Direct imaging - photographing a planet's own light right next to its far brighter host - normally only works for bright, massive planets, so Beta Pictoris d is a milestone: it is about 100 times fainter than the famous Beta Pic b and, corrected for distance, the faintest exoplanet yet imaged from Earth. It is a gas giant of roughly 2.4 Jupiter masses (against ~10 for b and c) on a much wider orbit. The team spotted it with the Very Large Telescope's ERIS instrument, then found it lurking in archival VLT/SPHERE images going back 11 years; an independent group led by Aidan Gibbs (University of California) detected the same planet with JWST.", "why": "Beta Pictoris becomes only the second system, after HR 8799, with more than two directly imaged planets - a natural laboratory for comparing worlds born from the same disk, and a taste of what ESO's Extremely Large Telescope should routinely reach.", "thread_id": "2026-07-22-science-beta-pictoris-d-the-faintest-exoplanet-ever-dire", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-22", "event_date": "2026-07-15", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["University of Edinburgh", "ESO"], "entities": ["Beta Pictoris", "ESO", "Very Large Telescope", "JWST"]}
{"id": "2026-07-22-science-one-jwst-instrument-mode-two-atmosphere-fingerpr", "date": "2026-07-22", "stream": "science", "headline": "One JWST instrument mode, two atmosphere fingerprints for a hot Jupiter", "summary": "A phase-resolved cross-correlation technique extracts WASP-39 b's atmospheric metallicity and C/O ratio from a single archival JWST NIRSpec mode, instead of the usual multi-mode campaign.", "url": "https://arxiv.org/abs/2607.18409", "source_domain": "arxiv.org", "tier": "T1", "tags": ["preprint"], "topics": ["science"], "importance": 1, "display_body": "Reading an exoplanet atmosphere's metallicity (how enriched it is in elements heavier than hydrogen and helium) and its carbon-to-oxygen ratio - both clues to where in its disk the planet formed - usually demands several JWST instrument modes stitched across ~1-5 microns. This work shows both can be pulled from a single archival transit of the well-studied hot Jupiter WASP-39 b, taken with one NIRSpec mode, by importing a technique from ground-based astronomy: phase-resolved cross-correlation at the detector's native pixel resolution, which matches the full-resolution spectrum against molecular templates instead of collapsing it into a coarse light curve.", "why": "If one instrument mode can do the job, JWST can characterise more planet atmospheres per hour of scarce telescope time - a practical multiplier for the field.", "thread_id": "2026-07-22-science-one-jwst-instrument-mode-two-atmosphere-fingerpr", "first_seen_date": "2026-07-22", "event_date": "2026-07-21", "embedding_model": "bge-m3", "emb": "", "affiliations": ["University of Maryland", "University of Chicago", "Johns Hopkins APL"], "entities": ["WASP-39b", "JWST", "University of Maryland"]}
